D ITS BIBLIOGRAPHY FOR CHAPTER 15 -- tAPPENDIX D EGYPTIAN TOMBS WITH AEGEAN DATA: LIST AND ITS BIBLIOGRAPHY FOR CHAPTER 15 -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis pioneering work revises our notions of the origins and early development of textiles in Europe and the Near East. Using innovative linguistic techniques, along with methods from palaeobiology and other fields, it shows that spinning and pattern weaving began far earlier than has been supposed. Prehistoric Textiles made an unsurpassed leap in the social and cultural understanding of textiles in humankind's early history. Cloth making was an industry that consumed more time and effort, and was more culturally significant to prehistoric cultures, than anyone assumed before the book's publication. The textile industry is in fact older than pottery--and perhaps even older than agriculture and stockbreeding. It probably consumed far more hours of labor per year, in temperate climates, than did pottery and food production put together. And this work was done primarily by women. Up until the Industrial Revolution, and into this century in many peasant societies, women spent every available moment spinning, weaving, and sewing. The author, Elizabeth Wayland Barber, demonstrates command of an almost unbelievably disparate array of disciplines--from historical linguistics to archaeology and paleobiology, from art history to the practical art of weaving. Her passionate interest in the subject matter leaps out on every page. Barber, a professor of linguistics and archaeology, developed expert sewing and weaving skills as a small girl under her mother's tutelage. One could say she had been born and raised to write this book. Because modern textiles are almost entirely made by machines, we have difficulty appreciating how time-consuming and important the premodern textile industry was. This book opens our eyes to this crucial area of prehistoric human culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  a3rd millennium BC.  aAlkanet.  aAncient Peru.  aAnimal fiber.  aAwning.  aBackpack.  aBeige.  aBronze Age.  aBull-leaping.  aCentral Europe.  aCharioteer (tank).  aChild care.  aColor scheme.  aContainment.  aCopying.  aCotton gin.  aCultigen.  aDissident.  aEarthen floor.  aEastern Europe.  aEgyptology.  aEl-Lahun.  aEnglish phonology.  aEpigraphy.  aFolk etymology.  aFreeman (Colonial).  aFurniture.  aGleaning.  aGlove.  aHagia Triada sarcophagus.  aHallstatt.  aHatshepsut.  aHerringbone (cloth).  aHis Family.  aHorsehair.  aHuman head.  aIngenuity.  aIron Age.  aKenaf.  aKilt.  aKleos.  aLace.  aLascaux.  aLeather.  aLong hair.  aLoom.  aMagdalenian.  aMastaba.  aMordant.  aMount Ararat.  aNahal Hemar.  aNarva culture.  aNebamun.  aNeedlework.  aNeolithic.  aPalmette.  aPan-Arabism.  aPfister (firm).  aPhaistos.  aPliers.  aPolicy.  aPottery.  aProcession.  aPseudomorph.  aQuedlinburg.  aR/T.  aRegnal year.  aRemittance.  aRoving.  aRuminant.  aRunning.  aRussian architecture.  aSaddle blanket.  aSafflower.  aScale insect.  aSesklo.  aSexism.  aShoulder (road).  aShroud.  aSilver spoon.  aSpecial effect.  aSpindle whorl.  aSupply chain.  aSzékesfehérvár.  aTapestry.  aTartrazine.  aTechnical analysis.  aTextile.  aThutmose I.  aTiryns.  aTunic.  aTutankhamun.  aTwill.  aVase.  aVerb.  aWarp and woof.  aWeaving.  aWest Semitic.  aWhey.  aWool.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt